Build Campaign Heatmaps with Kibana & ATT&CK Navigator
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Set up Kibana dashboards to track and visualize attack activity
Build interactive heatmaps for campaign data visualization
Use ATT&CK Navigator to correlate activities and identify high-risk areas
Analyze threat patterns using open-source intelligence tools
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of cybersecurity concepts
Familiarity with Linux command line
Knowledge of MITRE ATT&CK framework fundamentals
Understanding of JSON data structures
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides a Linux-based cloud machine for this lab. Click Start Lab to access your environment. The machine comes with a bare metal installation, so you'll install all required tools during the lab exercises.

Task 1: Set Up Kibana Dashboards to Track Attack Activity
Subtask 1.1: Install Elasticsearch and Kibana
Install Java (required for Elasticsearch):

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y openjdk-11-jdk
java -version
Download and install Elasticsearch:

wget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/elasticsearch/elasticsearch-8.11.0-amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i elasticsearch-8.11.0-amd64.deb
Configure Elasticsearch for single-node setup:

sudo nano /etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml
Add these configurations:

cluster.name: attack-analysis
node.name: node-1
network.host: localhost
http.port: 9200
discovery.type: single-node
xpack.security.enabled: false
Start Elasticsearch:

sudo systemctl enable elasticsearch
sudo systemctl start elasticsearch
sudo systemctl status elasticsearch
Download and install Kibana:

wget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/kibana/kibana-8.11.0-amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i kibana-8.11.0-amd64.deb
Configure Kibana:

sudo nano /etc/kibana/kibana.yml
Add these settings:

server.port: 5601
server.host: "localhost"
elasticsearch.hosts: ["http://localhost:9200"]
Start Kibana:

sudo systemctl enable kibana
sudo systemctl start kibana
sudo systemctl status kibana
